	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Calls for comprehensive review of CARICOM agro-food sector strategies </h1>

			
			<h4>
												23 February 2014
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to a briefing paper published by the FAO Subregional Office for the Caribbean, “CARICOM’s food import bill sky-rocketed from US$2.08 billion in 2000 to US$4.25 billion in 2011.” Four countries account for “over two-thirds by value of the food import bill”. These are:</p>
<ul>

<li>Jamaica: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 21% – US$913 million;</li>

<li>Trinidad and Tobago: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 20% – US$833 million; </li>

<li>Haiti: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 19% – US$802 million; </li>

<li>Bahamas: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 9% – US$393 million.</li>

</ul>
<p><b>Top 10 Caribbean food and agricultural imports in 2011</b></p><table class="renderedtable" border="1" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0">
<tr>
<td width="168" valign="top">  Product&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
