</table>
<p>Source: FAOSTAT 2013, cited in FAO, ‘CARICOM food import bill’ (see below), p. 2.</p><p>According to the paper, “in 2010, only 12.7% of total food imports were sourced from within the Caribbean”, compared to 17.3% in 2000. This is despite “the value of intra-regional food trade” having “grown by 48% during the period 2000 to 2012, from US$302 million to US$449 million”. In terms of the biggest participants in intra-regional trade in agro-food products, “Jamaica (31%), Barbados (13%), Trinidad and Tobago (11%), Saint Lucia (11%) and Guyana (8%) continued to dominate.”</p><p>The paper noted that “the value of CARICOM rice imports increased by 92% in a little over a decade, from US$125 million in 2000 to US$240 million in 2011.” Haiti and Jamaica accounted for 49% and 29% respectively of the region’s rice imports.</p><p>This trend in growing food imports and the declining proportion of intra-regional trade to meet the CARICOM member states’ import needs is a matter of growing concern recorded in regional press articles. In December 2013, the Jamaican government announced that it planned to table legislation in parliament “to require public-sector entities to ensure that a minimum portion of the food they purchase [is] locally produced”. The Agriculture Minister, Roger Clarke, argued that “while some sustainable level of import is necessary, Jamaicans should not buy into the prescription of some multilateral companies, which are encouraging the country to focus on service rather than on industries.” Similarly, the government of Barbados less than a week later “appealed to supermarkets and hotels to give more support to the local agricultural sector”, but stopped short of advocating import controls.</p><p>According to the FAO paper, growing levels of extra-regional imports are crowding out local agro-food processors. If this situation of local production being displaced is to be reversed, then “severe competitiveness constraints at all points of the food value chain” will need to be addressed. The paper lists several such constraints. There are also concerns over the health implications of growing levels of processed food imports, with non-communicable diseases such as diabetes, hypertension and coronary problems increasing. The report notes that the incidence of men in CARICOM being overweight rose from 5% to over 25% between 1970 and 2011, while the incidence for women increased from 20% to over 50%.</p><p>According to the FAO analysis, “the region needs a comprehensive strategy which invests in more efficient food production systems, import substitution and consumer education, and brings together the private and public sector.”</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>FAO Subregional Office for the Caribbean, ‘CARICOM food import bill, food security and nutrition’, <i>Issue Brief</i> no. 5, October 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/fsnforum/caribbean/sites/caribbean/files/files/Briefs/Food%20Import%20brief%20.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/fsnforum/caribbean/sites/caribbean/files/files/Briefs...</a></p><p><i>Jamaican Gleaner</i>, ‘Food-security bill could mandate state entities to buy Jamaican’, 12 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20131212/lead/lead3.html" target="_self">http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20131212/lead/lead3.html</a></p><p><i>Jamaica Gleaner</i>, ‘Barbados minister tells businesses - Let us eat what we produce’, 18 December 2013</p><p>
<a href="http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20131218/business/business81.html" target="_self">http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20131218/business/business81.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>In most countries in the Caribbean, the proportion of the working population still engaged in agriculture is low and falling, while in many states agricultural competitiveness is weak. However, the importance of the sector reaches beyond what would be indicated by its share of GDP and employment alone. Socially, it is often the poorest sections of the community that are dependent on agriculture. Economically, as the FAO report points out, foreign exchange spent on food imports is not available for other, more developmentally strategic goods and services.</p><p>But what to do? Agricultural products are already generally much more heavily protected from imports than other goods in many Caribbean states, and national EPA liberalisation strategies, for example, either exclude or ‘backload’ key agricultural goods (i.e. only implement them at the end of the agreed tariff phase-down period). The Jamaican government plan to require state institutions to purchase minimum shares of imports will have an impact if the root problem is lack of demand, but not if it is lack of supply (arising from an ageing rural population or from low investment).</p><p>One view is that Caribbean agriculture is at a critical point of transition. The once-dominant export sectors that exported under trade preferences are declining, but have not yet been sufficiently replaced by dynamic new producers able either to export to niche markets or capable of displacing imports even under the current substantial levels of protection. Temporary fixes may well be required. But in the longer term, only stronger policy support for investment into efficient production of foods that Caribbean consumers want to buy in preference to imports will reverse the decline in agriculture in the Caribbean.</p>
		</div>
		
